snippet.textDisplay:
"What kid read Steven King books?"

I started with RL Stine, but moved on to Steven King when I ran out of Fear Street novels in the school library. I actually remember asking for a whole bunch of them for Christmas. Not a one was appropriate for my age, but oh well.

Around 10-12 I was also a horror movie fanatic and wanted to make SFX makeup for them. I cherished the book that had the Children of the Corn short story. And to this day the ridiculousness of the short story about a really long finger in a sink drain has haunted me with it's sheer stupidity.

All traditional Hallmark Christmas-romance movies can be explained like this:

·girl flies to Large City and meets a rich widow with an 8 year old daughter and a maid
·blablabla girl goes to rich widows mansion and bakes cookies with his daughter
·flirting
·girl goes to her hotel and FaceTimes her bff while eating the cookies she took because that's the only good she has
·uh oh! girl can't fly home because of a blizzard! guess she'll have to fall in love with rich man before her rescheduled flight time!
·they go ice skating with the daughter and the girl can skate like a professional
·blabla they get engaged and she never goes home
